n order to shed light on the nature of the interpretive interfaces, Logical Form and Phonetic Form, and their role in the syntactic computation. The chapters in this volume collectively contribute to a better understanding of the mapping from syntax to PF on the one hand, especially issues concerning prosody and Spell-Out, and semantic interpretation at LF on the other, including interpretive and architectural issues of more conceptual nature. Apart from careful case studies and specific data analysis for a number of languages, the material contained here also has repercussions for Phase Theory in general, theoretical underpinnings as well as modifications of syntactic mechanisms.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aGenerative Syntax. 4aPhase. 4aSyntax. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aMinimalist Program.  aSyntax.1 aGeraci, Carlo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrohmann, Kleanthes K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrohmann, Kleanthes K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHaiden, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKallulli, Dalina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOtt, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPutnam, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaleemi, Anjum, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScheer, Tobias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStroik, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTokizaki, Hisao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToyoshima, Takashi, 